Wharf to Wharf: 2018

Aaron Ferrucci

July 27, 2018

Introduction

The Wharf to Wharf race happens every July in Santa Cruz. The mostly flat, 6-mile course hugs the coastline between Santa Cruz and Capitola. The race has grown in popularity since its beginning in 1973, with more than 13,000 registered participants in 2018.

Race results are available online. You can look up runners’ results by bib number, name, city and state. This is ok, but it’s not very handy for anyone wanting to do real data analysis.

I’ve written some code to scrape the data from the results page, clean it up, and plot some interesting things. The code is available on github; if you see a problem, fork my repo, fix it, and do a pull request!

Summary of results

  • There were 13425 participants in the 2015 event
  • The average age of a participant is about 42.
  • There are more female participants than male, with a F:M ratio of about 1.5:1.
  • Overwhelmingly, participants are from the USA. And almost all (97.8%) are from California.
  • There are some anomalies in the data - 93 participants with age 0, 49 participants who started before the official start time of 8:30AM (but maybe this is real data), etc. It’s not the messiest data set I’ve seen.
  • Males tend to be faster than females. This is especially pronounced in the top 100 ranks.
